# Field MVP Workflow — Chunk Discipline

This rule governs every chunk of the REMI 1.0 Field MVP plan
(`docs/implementation-plans/remi-1.0-field-mvp-plan.md`). It exists
because between 2026-05-22 and 2026-05-23 the assistant made a
specific class of mistakes more than once, and the user explicitly
demanded these be prevented going forward.

## The mistakes this rule prevents

1. **Claiming a chunk is SHIPPED when only its docs are on `main`.** On
   2026-05-22 the assistant merged a docs-only PR (#154) that flipped
   Chunk 1.2's plan-doc status to "SHIPPED" while the actual Chunk 1.2
   code (`7cc0487 feat(stripe): wire StripeProvider + PaymentSheet`)
   sat on a local unmerged branch. Then the assistant told the user
   "Phase 1 Chunk 1.2 is fully shipped and published" — which was
   false. The code only existed on the user's laptop.

2. **Decoupling plan-doc changes from code changes.** The docs update
   was branched off `main` directly while code work continued on a
   stacked feature branch. The work branch's tree never got the plan
   update, so when the cloud agent read the plan from the workspace it
   saw the pre-SHIPPED version (1779 lines, no Chunk 1.3 section)
   instead of the current SHIPPED version on `main` (1954 lines).
   Result: the agent operated against a stale tree.

3. **Stacking unmerged work without a bundling discipline.** Phase 1
   accumulated four stacked FE branches (1.1, 1.1.1, 1.2, 1.3), all
   local-only, none PR'd, while the plan doc on `main` already
   described them as in various states. Each stacked branch was real
   working code that had been smoke-tested, but invisible to anyone
   reading `main`.

4. **Making the user do git operations.** The user has stated
   explicitly and repeatedly: *"do everything for me, I need to just
   be doing prompts."* Every git command (branch, commit, push, PR
   open, PR merge, submodule pointer bump) is the assistant's job.
   The user pastes prompts; the assistant runs the rest end-to-end.

## The non-negotiable rules

### 1. PR mechanics for every chunk

For each Field MVP chunk, **the assistant runs the full git lifecycle
without prompting** the user for any step. The lifecycle is:

   a. Cut a feature branch off current `origin/main` (or the latest
      stacked tip if the chunk explicitly stacks — see §7). Use
      `./scripts/check-branch-chunk.sh --create <branch-name>`. See
      `branch-hygiene.mdc`.
   b. Make the code changes for that chunk.
   c. Update `docs/implementation-plans/remi-1.0-field-mvp-plan.md`
      **in the SAME branch** — flip the chunk status from `DRAFT` /
      `IN-PROGRESS` to `SHIPPED`, add the post-execution callout,
      draft the next chunk if hand-off applies. **NEVER ship the
      plan-doc update in a separate PR from the code.** If the chunk
      is genuinely a doc-only chunk (e.g., drafting future-phase
      prompts with no code), that's fine — but then the plan-doc PR
      is not allowed to claim any code chunk is `SHIPPED`.
   d. Update `docs/DEVELOPMENT-LOG.md` in the same branch. See
      `documentation.mdc`.
   e. Stage everything, commit with a focused message, push with
      `-u origin HEAD`.
   f. Open the PR via `gh pr create` (`gh` is authorized for submodule
      PRs per the umbrella's `remi-monorepo-submodules.mdc`).
   g. Wait for CI green, merge via
      `gh pr merge <num> --squash --delete-branch`.
   h. If REMITechnician changes were part of a multi-repo chunk (BE +
      FE), repeat a–g in REMIBackend (and any other touched
      submodule) — and only after every submodule PR is merged, bump
      the REMI-Monorepo umbrella pointer per `AGENTS.md` (cut a
      feature branch on the monorepo, commit the submodule pointer
      update, push, open PR via `ManagePullRequest` or `gh`, CI
      green, squash-merge).

The user should not see any of these commands except in the final
"merged, you're good" status report.

### 2. State accuracy — plan label must match git state

The plan-doc's chunk status labels MUST match the actual git state of
`origin/main`:

| Plan label | Means | Verify by |
|---|---|---|
| `SHIPPED` | Code is on `origin/main` AND smoke-tested AND post-execution callout written | `git log origin/main -- <code file>` shows the commit |
| `IN-PROGRESS` | Code is on a pushed branch but not yet merged | `git ls-remote origin <branch>` returns the SHA, `gh pr view <num>` shows the PR |
| `DRAFT` | Hand-off prompt written, no code yet | only plan-doc text exists |
| `ON-BRANCH` | Code is committed locally but **NOT** pushed to a PR | local-only branch, no remote PR — this label is a red flag, see §7 |

**Before flipping a chunk to `SHIPPED`, the assistant MUST verify the
code is actually on `origin/main` of every affected repo** by running
the verification commands above. Saying "X is shipped" when X is only
in a docs PR or only on a local branch is forbidden.

### 3. Hand-off prep — run BEFORE pasting any chunk prompt

Before the user pastes a chunk prompt to a cloud agent (or any other
external agent), the assistant MUST run this 3-step check and report
the result in one short status block:

   a. **Verify `main` has the plan-doc state describing the chunk.**
      `git log origin/main -- docs/implementation-plans/remi-1.0-field-mvp-plan.md`
      should show the merge that added/updated the chunk section.
   b. **Verify the working branch is rebased onto `origin/main`** so
      the plan + code live in the same tree. If the user's current
      branch is N commits behind `origin/main`, rebase or merge it up
      before any hand-off.
   c. **Verify no previous chunk's code is stuck on a local-only
      branch.** Run `git branch --no-merged origin/main` in every
      relevant repo. If anything is stacked but unmerged, run the §1
      lifecycle to land it FIRST — then return to the hand-off.

The hand-off prompt itself should still carry the full chunk spec
(self-contained, no required external context) — but the tree the
agent reads from must AGREE with the prompt, not contradict it.

### 4. Metro-first iteration for Phase 1

Phase 1 chunks default to **Metro dev-client**, NOT `eas update` OTA.
Per `eas-build-versioning.mdc` Step 0:

   - JS-only change against a binary that already has the native
     module → Metro dev-client absorbs it. No build credit spent. No
     OTA bundle that can silently fail to land on the device.
   - Native package added / removed / `app.json` plugins changed →
     `eas build --profile development --platform ios`.
   - Production-readiness work → `eas build --profile preview`.

The 2026-05-22 OTA pivot during Chunk 1.2 (bundle silently failed to
land on the device) was the trigger for this default. Reverting to
OTA-first without a written justification in the chunk's
post-execution callout is not allowed in Phase 1.

### 5. Table-of-Contents update on every chunk addition

Every time a new `## Chunk X.Y — ...` heading lands in
`docs/implementation-plans/remi-1.0-field-mvp-plan.md`, the Table of
Contents at the top of the same doc MUST get a matching `- [Chunk X.Y — ...](#chunk-xy--...)`
entry in the same commit. If the chunk supersedes the trailing
`_(pending)_` placeholder line (e.g., the old "Chunks 1.4 – 5.x
_(pending)_" entry once Chunk 1.4 is drafted), update the range so
the placeholder still bounds the unfinished work correctly.

This is non-optional because the docs site renders the TOC as the
primary navigation for a 2,000+ line plan doc. A chunk that exists in
the body but not in the TOC is **invisible** to the user trying to
copy-paste the prompt — they have to either Cmd-F through the whole
file or know the chunk number a priori. Either way, the published doc
is broken.

Procedure when adding a chunk section to the plan doc:

  a. Insert the `## Chunk X.Y — <title>` heading + body in the
     appropriate spot (preserving section order: 0.x, 1.x, 2.x, ...).
  b. **In the same edit, add the TOC entry under "Chunk detail"** in
     the order it appears in the body. Match the heading text exactly
     (the auto-generated GitHub-style anchor must resolve — em-dash
     → `--`, backticks dropped, lowercase, spaces → `-`).
  c. Update the trailing `_(pending)_` placeholder so the unfinished
     range advances. For example: after drafting Chunk 1.4 the old
     `Chunks 1.4 – 5.x _(pending)_` line becomes `Chunks 2.x – 5.x
     _(pending — drafted as each Phase begins)_`.
  d. Spot-check the new anchor by reading the post-sync file at
     `Docs/docs/repos/technician/implementation-plans/<file>.md` and
     confirming the heading slug GitHub will generate matches the
     `#chunk-x-y-...` href in the TOC. (No live URL to click — see §6.)

The user has called out missed TOC updates THREE times in this plan's
history (2026-05-22 — Chunk 1.2; 2026-05-23 — Chunk 1.3; 2026-05-23 —
Chunk 1.4). The fix has been the same each time: re-edit the TOC,
re-PR, re-sync. This rule exists so the next chunk doesn't make it
four. If you find yourself committing a `## Chunk` section addition
to this plan, **STOP and re-read this section** before pushing.

### 6. Publish-and-verify: confirm the sync lands on `Docs/main`

Every plan-doc change must reach the published docs source on
`Docs/main` (= `JaceG/REMI-Documentation` on GitHub) within the same
working session — otherwise the user can't pull up the hand-off prompt
without first cloning the Tech repo locally. The pipeline is automatic
but only fires under specific conditions, and the assistant MUST
verify the sync commit actually landed each time.

**The pipeline (what really happens):**

1. **`REMITechnician/.github/workflows/notify-docs.yml`** fires on every
   push to `main` that touches `README.md`, `docs/DEVELOPMENT-LOG.md`,
   or anything under `docs/implementation-plans/**`. It posts a
   `repository_dispatch sync-docs` to `JaceG/REMI-Documentation`.
2. **`Docs/.github/workflows/sync-repo-docs.yml`** receives that dispatch,
   sparse-checks-out every submodule's `docs/` + `README.md` +
   `DEMO-CODE.md`, copies them into `Docs/docs/repos/<repo>/...`, and
   commits `Sync repo docs (automated)` on `Docs`'s `main`.
3. **GitHub Pages on `JaceG/REMI-Documentation`** auto-publishes
   from `main` / `/docs` (built-in Pages, no extra workflow). Once
   step 2's commit lands, the new content is served automatically.
   There is no Cloudflare in this pipeline and there is no custom
   domain wired up — `https://jaceg.github.io/REMI-Documentation/` is
   the only live URL, and the user has expressed that even that URL
   is not part of the verification path because the agent should
   trust the sync-commit landing as proof.

**Anti-hallucination guard:** prior versions of this rule and several
chunk callouts (Chunks 1.4, 1.5) claimed the pipeline ended at
`https://maxitechremi.app` on Cloudflare Pages. **Neither exists.**
`dig +short maxitechremi.app` returns nothing. There is no
`wrangler.toml`, no `_headers`, no Cloudflare deploy workflow, and no
`CNAME` file anywhere in `Docs/`. If a future agent finds itself
about to write "verified live at maxitechremi.app" — **STOP**. The
correct phrasing names the `Docs/main` sync commit.

**The assistant's obligation per plan-doc change:**

   a. **The plan-doc edit must land on `REMITechnician/main`** — not on a
      side branch, not in a draft PR. The `notify-docs.yml` trigger only
      fires on push to `main` per the workflow's `on.push` filter. A
      stacked or draft branch never fires the webhook.
   b. **After the PR merges**, verify the Docs sync ran:
        cd /Users/jacegalloway/Documents/codebases/REMI-Monorepo/Docs && \
          git fetch origin && git log --oneline origin/main -5 | head -3
      Look for a recent `Sync repo docs (automated)` commit timestamp
      newer than the plan-doc PR's merge timestamp. If not seen within
      ~2 minutes, manually trigger via the GitHub UI:
      `Docs` repo → Actions → "Sync Repo Docs" → "Run workflow".
   c. **Verify the synced file's content matches the source.** Pull
      `Docs/main` and `diff`:
        diff <(cat REMITechnician/docs/implementation-plans/<file>.md) \
             <(cat Docs/docs/repos/technician/implementation-plans/<file>.md)
      Should be empty (or differ only by trailing newline). If the synced
      copy lags more than two minutes behind, the sync may have failed —
      check the Actions log on the `Docs` repo.
   d. **For brand-new doc files** (e.g., a fresh plan), confirm
      `Docs/docs/assets/docs-config.js` has an entry registering the file
      with the docs site nav. The sync workflow copies content but does
      NOT add nav entries; that's a one-time hand edit on `Docs`. The
      Field MVP plan got its entry on 2026-05-22 (Docs commit `35e4eb5`).
      If a new plan file appears in `Docs/docs/repos/.../*.md` with no
      `docs-config.js` entry, it's still reachable via direct file path
      but is INVISIBLE in the rendered nav — add the entry in the same
      session.
   e. **Confirm the sync BEFORE telling the user the prompt is ready
      to copy.** The acceptance phrasing is: *"Chunk X.Y prompt is
      synced to `Docs/main` at commit `<sha>` — the file is at
      `Docs/docs/repos/technician/implementation-plans/<file>.md`
      and GitHub Pages serves it automatically from there."*
      Saying "the prompt is drafted" without verifying the
      `Sync repo docs (automated)` commit actually landed on
      `Docs/main` is the same class of mistake as the §1 "shipped
      without code" failure.

The user has stated this requirement explicitly: *"don't forget to do
everything it takes to get it on the docs website for me to copy and
paste, if you need to add that to the rule so you don't forget from now
on please do."* (2026-05-23.) And the corollary, stated 2026-05-23
after the assistant burned a session hallucinating a Cloudflare site:
*"They don't exist and don't need to be replaced because it takes care
of itself to get on the github pages when updated."* Failing to
verify the sync after a plan-doc edit is a §1-class breach; inventing
a URL or hosting provider to make the verification statement sound
better is a separate, worse breach.

### 7. Hand-off prompt structure (placement + fence + copy-paste integrity)

Every `## Chunk X.Y — ...` section in
`docs/implementation-plans/remi-1.0-field-mvp-plan.md` follows a
fixed internal order, and the hand-off prompt block has a fixed
fence shape. Both are non-negotiable — the user copy-pastes these
prompts directly off the rendered file on `Docs/main` (auto-served
via GitHub Pages, per §6) into fresh agent chats, and a malformed
prompt = a broken hand-off.

**Placement: hand-off prompt goes near the TOP of the chunk, not the bottom.**

The canonical chunk-section order, established by every prior chunk
(0.1 → 1.4), is:

  a. `## Chunk X.Y — <title>` heading
  b. One-paragraph intro callout (blockquote, `> **Why this chunk exists:** ...` or similar)
  c. `### Hand-off prompt (paste into ...)` — the full prompt block
  d. `### Goal`
  e. `### Why this chunk` / `### Why this chunk before <next>`
  f. `### What lands in the commits`
  g. `### Acceptance criteria`
  h. `### Out-of-scope for this chunk (do NOT do these)`
  i. Any remaining subsections (PR strategy, file touch list,
     schema sanity check, etc.)

The user opens the doc, jumps to the chunk via the TOC, and the
first thing they see beneath the chunk heading is the copy-pasteable
prompt. Anything else (Goal, Why, Acceptance) is reference material
for the *executing* agent — it gets surfaced when the agent reads
the chunk on its end, NOT when the user copies the prompt. Putting
the prompt at the bottom forces the user to scroll past the entire
spec to get to the copyable text, which is the opposite of the
"one-click hand-off" the plan-doc shape is designed for.

If you find yourself appending a `### Hand-off prompt` subsection
AFTER `### Out-of-scope` or `### PR strategy`, **STOP** — move it
above `### Goal` before commit. (Chunk 1.5's first draft, 2026-05-23,
made this exact mistake. The user caught it. This rule exists so the
NEXT chunk doesn't.)

**Fence: use 4 backticks for the outer fence whenever the prompt body contains any code blocks.**

Hand-off prompts almost always contain inner fenced code blocks —
`psql` snippets, `git` commands, shell pipelines, JSON, TS skeletons.
If the outer fence is also 3 backticks, the FIRST inner ` ``` ` closes
the outer fence prematurely. The docs site then renders the prompt as
several disjoint code blocks instead of one contiguous block, and the
COPY button next to the first block only grabs the partial prefix.
The user gets a truncated prompt with no warning.

The fix is mechanical: **use 4 backticks (` ```` `) for the outer
fence** any time the prompt body has even ONE inner 3-backtick block.
Chunk 1.4 followed this pattern (line 1982: `````); Chunk 1.5's first
draft did not, which is what triggered the user's "I can't copy it
all" feedback on 2026-05-23.

A safe default is "always use 4 backticks for hand-off prompt outer
fences." It costs nothing on prompts with no inner code, and it's the
only shape that survives the inner-code case. If you're already using
4-backtick outer fences uniformly, you never have to think about
this again.

Procedure when authoring or editing a hand-off prompt:

  a. Open the prompt with `` ```` `` (four backticks) on its own line.
  b. Close with `` ```` `` (four backticks) on its own line.
  c. Inside, any code samples (psql, git, shell, ts) use ordinary
     3-backtick fences — they nest cleanly inside the 4-backtick
     outer.
  d. After the prompt lands on `main` and `Sync repo docs (automated)`
     fires on `Docs/main` (per §6), open the synced file directly:
     `Docs/docs/repos/technician/implementation-plans/<file>.md`.
     Locate the chunk's hand-off prompt and confirm the outer
     4-backtick fence opens and closes around the *entire* prompt
     body (from "You are Chunk X.Y of ..." through the closing
     "Sign-off message back to the user" line) — with no inner
     3-backtick block sitting between the outer fences as a
     same-level sibling. If the fences are misaligned, GitHub
     will render the prompt as several disjoint blocks; re-edit,
     bump the fence to 4 backticks, re-PR, re-verify.

The plan-doc is the primary artifact this rule governs, but the same
shape rules apply to any future doc that publishes copy-pasteable
agent prompts (e.g., `pdf-implementation-plans/agent-prompts/*.md`).

### 8. Stacking discipline

If a chunk genuinely depends on a previous chunk's unmerged code
(e.g., Chunk 1.3 stacks on 1.2's PaymentSheet wiring), exactly **one**
of two patterns is allowed:

   a. **Land each chunk's PR as it completes** (preferred). The next
      chunk's branch then cuts off the new `main`, not off the
      stacked tip. This keeps `main` and the plan-doc honest at every
      step.
   b. **One bundle PR for a whole sub-phase**, with an explicit
      checklist in the PR body covering every chunk inside it AND the
      plan-doc updates for all of them. The bundle PR is opened the
      moment the FIRST chunk in the bundle is code-complete, not
      after all of them are done — that way it can't be forgotten.
      The plan-doc must label every chunk in the bundle as
      `IN-PROGRESS` (linked to the open PR), never `SHIPPED`, until
      the bundle merges.

The **forbidden third pattern** is "let stacked branches accumulate
locally while telling the user they're shipped." That's what
happened 2026-05-22 → 2026-05-23 and is the exact failure this rule
exists to prevent. If the assistant ever finds itself about to write
"Chunk X is shipped" while `git ls-remote origin` doesn't show the
corresponding PR, STOP — re-read §2.

### 9. One agent per Phase — prompt-writing implications

Each Phase has ONE dedicated executing-agent chat that runs ALL
chunks in that Phase sequentially. Phase 0 chunks ran in one agent.
Phase 1 chunks ran in another. Phase 2's Chunk 2.1 + 2.2 + 2.3 all
run in the SAME Phase 2 agent. **The user starts a fresh agent
ONLY when crossing a Phase boundary** (Phase 1 → Phase 2 = new
agent; Chunk 2.1 → Chunk 2.2 = SAME agent). This is stated
explicitly in `## Next steps` item 11 of the plan doc: *"one agent
per Phase, chunks run sequentially inside that agent's chat."*

**Why this matters for the prompt-writer (us):**

The FIRST chunk of a Phase (e.g., Chunk 2.1) IS a fresh chat. Its
prompt should open with "You are starting a fresh Cursor chat..." and
pull in all foundational context — repo paths, prior shipped work,
schema baseline, workflow rules, etc.

Every SUBSEQUENT chunk of the same Phase (e.g., Chunk 2.2) opens
INSIDE an already-loaded chat. The agent already has, in active
context:

  - All workflow rules (loaded once per chat by globs/`alwaysApply`).
  - All files it read or built in prior chunks of the same Phase.
  - All schema migrations it applied (and the `psql` outputs it
    pasted into earlier turns).
  - All test baselines from prior chunks.
  - The Phase's running mental model (what `pending` vs `failed`
    means, what the cadence enum does, what the existing service
    layout looks like, etc.).

Within-Phase chunk prompts therefore should:

  a. **Drop the "fresh Cursor chat" framing.** Open with: "You are
     Chunk X.Y of the REMI 1.0 Field MVP Plan — `<title>`. This is
     the next chunk in the Phase N agent's sequence (Chunk X.(Y-1)
     shipped via `<repo>` PR #ZZZ, squash `<sha>`)." Do NOT pretend
     the chat is fresh — the agent scrolls up, sees its own work
     product from the prior chunk, and the false framing makes
     everything below it suspect.
  b. **Skip "Read first" entries for files the agent already read or
     built in a prior chunk of the same Phase.** Re-listing them is
     token waste. ONLY list:
       - The plan-doc section for the NEW chunk (always — the binding
         spec must be re-read each chunk).
       - The post-execution callout / dev-log open-questions block
         from the prior chunk (the design decisions this chunk locks
         down live there; the agent benefits from re-anchoring).
       - NEW files this chunk touches for the first time (e.g.,
         Chunk 2.2's first touch of `src/cron/index.ts`).
  c. **Skip pre-flight items the agent already verified in a prior
     chunk.** The agent doesn't need to re-list the CARFAX enum
     names or re-check that `franchises.carfax_location_id` exists
     if it migrated it on chunk 1. ONLY list pre-flight that
     materially changed since the prior chunk:
       - Working-tree clean on the CURRENT `origin/main` (which
         advanced after the prior chunk merged).
       - NEW schema, NEW env vars, NEW corpus this chunk needs.
       - The NEW baseline test count (which moved after the prior
         chunk added tests).
  d. **Reference prior shipped work in ONE sentence by PR + SHA,
     not by re-explaining the architecture.** E.g.: "Chunk 2.1
     shipped `carfaxSubmissionService.submitForAppointment` via
     REMIBackend PR #110 (`1ddb117`). This chunk extends it with
     a retry counter and adds a cron sweep that delegates per-row
     through the same entry point." The agent re-reads the prior
     chunk's section in the plan doc for the rest.
  e. **Workflow / branch / PR rule reminders collapse to one
     sentence:** "All workflow rules from Chunk N.1 still apply
     (`field-mvp-workflow.mdc`, `branch-hygiene.mdc`,
     `architecture.mdc`); cut the new branch off the latest
     `origin/main` of each touched repo." No need to re-enumerate
     the same eight rules from the Phase opener.

**What this looks like in practice:**

| Phase opener (Chunk N.1) | Mid-Phase chunk (Chunk N.{2+}) |
|---|---|
| "You are starting a fresh Cursor chat. There is no prior context..." | "You are Chunk N.M. Chunk N.(M-1) shipped via PR #XXX (`<sha>`); this chunk extends it." |
| 7–8 "Read first" items including foundational repos | 2–3 "Read first" items: new chunk's plan section, prior chunk's open-questions callout, NEW files only |
| 5–7 pre-flight items including schema baseline + creds decision | 2–3 pre-flight items: clean tree on advanced `main`, NEW corpus needed, NEW baseline test count |
| Workflow + branch + PR rules listed in full | One-line reminder pointing back to the Phase opener's rule reads |

A mid-Phase chunk prompt should be **30–50% smaller** than its Phase
opener. If you find yourself writing "You are starting a fresh
Cursor chat" or "1. The full Chunk X.Y section... 2. The Phase N
sub-bullet block... 3. `<file the agent built last chunk>` ..." for
any chunk 2-through-N within a Phase, **STOP and trim** before the
PR opens.

**Edge case — Phase boundary crossings:** if the user explicitly
states they're starting a fresh agent at a chunk that isn't `N.1`
(e.g., "Phase 2 stalled, I'm restarting it at 2.3 in a new chat"),
treat that chunk as a Phase opener for prompt-writing purposes —
restore the full-context framing. The default assumption is
within-Phase continuity; the carve-out is only when the user names
the discontinuity.

## How the assistant uses this rule (per chunk)

1. **First action of the chunk:** run §3 (hand-off prep verification)
   against current `origin/main` of every relevant repo. Report what's
   actually on `main` vs what the plan claims, in one short status
   block, BEFORE doing any new work.
2. **During the chunk:** keep code AND plan-doc changes in the SAME
   branch (§1c). Don't open separate doc-only PRs unless the chunk
   itself is a doc-only chunk.
3. **End of the chunk:** run the full §1 lifecycle without prompting
   the user. Report the merged state in one final status block (table
   of `repo / PR # / status` is fine).
4. **Before any hand-off prompt is pasted:** re-run §3 to confirm the
   tree the next agent will read from matches the plan's claims;
   run §7 (hand-off prompt structure) to confirm the prompt block
   sits at the TOP of the chunk (above `### Goal`) and uses a
   4-backtick outer fence; run §5 (TOC) to confirm the chunk has a
   matching TOC entry; run §6 (publish-and-verify) to confirm the
   `Sync repo docs (automated)` commit landed on `Docs/main` and
   the synced file's outer fence still spans the full prompt body;
   run §9 (one-agent-per-Phase) to confirm the prompt's framing
   matches whether this is a Phase opener (Chunk N.1) or a
   mid-Phase chunk (Chunk N.{2+}) — mid-Phase prompts should drop
   the "fresh chat" framing and skip redundant `Read first` /
   pre-flight items the executing agent already has from the prior
   chunk. Saying "the prompt is drafted" without running all five
   checks is the same shape of mistake as the §1 "shipped without
   code" failure.

